# A filename is not the file

Module 01 showed you **where** files live. Now: what a file **is** — and **who** can touch it.

## Two separate things

A file is an **inode** (a numbered record) plus a **name** that points at it.

```
directory entry            inode #8214
┌──────────────┐          ┌────────────────────────┐
│ report.txt → 8214 ──────▶ owner · group · rwx bits │
│ notes.txt  → 8214 ──────▶ timestamps · size        │
└──────────────┘          │ ─▶ data blocks on disk    │
   names (in a dir)        └────────────────────────┘
                          metadata + data — NO name
```

The **name lives in the directory**; the **data + metadata live in the inode**.

## Why this matters

- **Links** — two names, one inode *(hard)* · a name that holds a path *(symbolic)*
- **Move / rename** is cheap — you edit a directory entry, not the data
- **Delete** removes a *name*; data goes when the **last** name does

## The permission model

Every inode carries an owner, a group, and **nine bits**:

```
   [ r w x ] [ r w x ] [ r w x ]
     owner     group     other
```

**This module:** create · view · copy/move · delete · links · file types · `chmod` · ownership.
